  {
    "type": "EXEGETICAL (ORIGINAL LANGUAGES)",
    "name": "Pulpit Commentary",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_sub_title",
        "text": "Verse 17.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " - ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_word",
        "text": "The brother of Caleb.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " The Hebrew does not inform us whether Othniel or Kenaz were Caleb's brother. But the fact (see note on Joshua 14:6) that Caleb was the son of Jephunneh leads to the idea that the latter is meant. Othniel was a valiant and capable commander, as we learn from ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Judges 3:9",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". Joshua 15:17",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "",
        "children": []
      }
    ]
  },
  {
    "type": "EXEGETICAL (ORIGINAL LANGUAGES)",
    "name": "Keil and Delitzsch Biblical Commentary on the Old Testament",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "Othniel took the town and received the promised prize. Othniel, according to ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Judges 3:9",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " the first judge of the Israelites after Joshua's death, is called כלב אחי קנז בּן, i.e., either \"the son of Kenaz (and) brother of Caleb,\" or \"the son of Kenaz the brother of Caleb.\" The second rendering is quite admissible (comp. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "2 Samuel 13:3",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "2 Samuel 13:32",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", with ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "1 Chronicles 2:13",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "), but the former is the more usual; and for this the Masorites have decided, since they have separated achi Caleb from ben-Kenaz by a tiphchah. And this is the correct one, as \"the son of Kenaz\" is equivalent to \"the Kenizzite\" (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Joshua 14:6",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "). According to ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Judges 1:13",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " and ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Judges 3:9",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", Othniel was Caleb's younger brother. Caleb gave him his daughter for a wife, as marriage with a brother's daughter was not forbidden in the law (see my Bibl. Archol. ii. 107, note 14).",
        "children": []
      }
    ]
  }
